Analysis of Electoral Bond Data¶

  • As per instruction of the Honorable Supreme Court of India, the State Bank of India (SBI) has submitted all the data regarding Electoral Bonds to Election Commission of India on 21/03/2024.
  • It includes the details of all bonds encashed between April 12, 2019, and January 24, 2024.
  • This data is publicly available on the website of ECI at www.eci.gov.in
    • Purchase_details (pdf)
    • Redemption_details (pdf)
    • These pdfs were converted to csv format using online utility and MS Excel
  • In this notebook, I will analyze the data and try to answer some salient questions.

🔎 Observations:

  • All the date columns are in object/string format which needs to be converted to pandas.datetime
  • We want denomination in int/float form for making calculation. Also denomination unit needs to be in Cr which is suitable for aggregation.
  • Bond Number should be converted to object because Prefix and Bond Number together gives a bond_id which can be used as unique identifier
  • Some columns need renaming for easy access
  • Columns to be deleted
    • Sr No, Reference No URN, Prefix, Bond\nNumber, Issue Branch Code, Issue Teller
    • Sr No, A/c no of Political party, Pay Branch code, Pay Teller
In [6]:
# Delete unnecessary columns
purchase_df.drop(columns=["Sr No.", "Reference No  (URN)", "Issue Branch Code", "Issue Teller"], inplace=True)

redeem_df.drop(columns=["Sr No.", "Account no. of\nPolitical Party", "Pay Branch\nCode", "Pay Teller"], inplace=True)

# Renaming columns as required
purchase_df.rename(columns={'Journal Date': 'j_date',
                            'Date of\nPurchase': 'p_date',
                            'Date of Expiry': 'e_date',
                            'Name of the Purchaser': 'purchaser',
                            'Prefix': 'prefix',
                            'Bond\nNumber': 'bond_number',
                            'Denominations': 'denominations',
                            'Status': 'status'}, inplace=True)

redeem_df.rename(columns={'Date of\nEncashment': 'encash_date',
                        'Name of the Political Party': 'party',
                        'Prefix': 'prefix',
                        'Bond\nNumber': 'bond_number',
                        'Denominations': 'encash_denominations'}, inplace=True)

# Changing date format from object to pd.datetime
purchase_df["j_date"] = pd.to_datetime(purchase_df["j_date"])
purchase_df["p_date"] = pd.to_datetime(purchase_df["p_date"])
purchase_df["e_date"] = pd.to_datetime(purchase_df["e_date"])

redeem_df["encash_date"] = pd.to_datetime(redeem_df["encash_date"])

# Changing denominations format
purchase_df.denominations = purchase_df.denominations.str.replace(",", "").astype("int")

redeem_df.encash_denominations = redeem_df.encash_denominations.str.replace(",", "").astype("int")

# Setting denomination unit to cr
purchase_df.denominations = purchase_df.denominations/10000000

redeem_df.encash_denominations = redeem_df.encash_denominations/10000000

# create a new column bond_id by combining prefix and bond number
purchase_df["bond_id"] = purchase_df.apply(lambda row: row["prefix"] + str(row["bond_number"]), axis=1)

redeem_df["bond_id"] = redeem_df.apply(lambda row: row["prefix"] + str(row["bond_number"]), axis=1)

# Delete prefix and bond number
purchase_df.drop(columns=["prefix", "bond_number"], inplace=True)

redeem_df.drop(columns=["prefix", "bond_number"], inplace=True)

Q. Create a table showing parties, agg redemption per year and total redemption.¶

# adding 'year' column for yearwise comparison
redeem_df["encash_year"] = redeem_df["encash_date"].dt.year

# Create a pivot table of yearwise donations received by parties
party_year = redeem_df.pivot_table(index="party", columns="encash_year",
                                   values="encash_denominations", aggfunc="sum")

# Merging partywise total to pivot table
party_year_total = party_year.merge(party_df["encash_denominations"], right_on=party_df.index, left_on=party_year.index)\
                .sort_values(by="encash_denominations", ascending=False).set_index("key_0")

Q. List Top 10 Donors for Top 5 parties¶

In [31]:
# A function to print top donors with respect to parties
def give_top_donors(party, df=merged_df, top=10):
    df_party = df[df.party == party].groupby("purchaser").denominations.sum()
    print(df_party.sort_values(ascending=False)[:top])

# Top 10 purchasers - partywise pie plot
top_purchasers = purchaser_total["denominations"].sort_values(ascending=False)[:10]

plt.figure(figsize=(10,20))
for i in range(10):
    plt.subplot(5,2,i+1)
    y = x[x.purchaser == top_purchasers.index[i]]
    y = y.groupby("party")["denominations"].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)
    plt.pie(y, autopct="%.2f%%")
    plt.title(f"{top_purchasers.index[i]} | {y.sum()} Cr", fontsize=8, fontweight="bold")
    plt.legend(y.index, bbox_to_anchor = (1.30, 0.6), loc='center right')
plt.suptitle("Partywise donation of Top 10 Purchasers", y=0.92, fontsize=12)
plt.savefig("top_10_purchaser_donation.png", dpi=400);
